<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="homework-expectations"
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Written homework expectations</title>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Grading and resubmissions</title>

    <p>Each exercise will be graded as
    <dl>
      <li><title>E (exemplary)</title>
      <p>which is 4 out of 4 points,</p>
      </li>
      <li><title>S (Satisfactory)</title>
      <p>which is 3 out of 4 points, or</p>
      </li>
      <li><title>NY (not yet)</title>
      <p>which is 0 out of 4 points.</p>
      </li>
    </dl>
    </p>

    <p>
      If you earn “S” or “NY”, you may revise and resubmit that
      exercise according to the following parameters:

      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Make sure you include the problem number.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Rewrite your entire solution as if you are doing it for
            the first time (unless I direct you otherwise).  You need
            not restate the question in full.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Write at least two sentences about what you learned from
            re-doing the problem.  For instance, you might write “I
            used to think that …, but now I understand that …”
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            You must have submitted an honest attempt on the problem
            by the original deadline (or requested an extension) in
            order to resubmit.  If you did not submit the exercise
            originally, see me to discuss options.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Each week, you may submit up to two revised exercises,
            within two weeks of their original due date.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Collaboration and Academic Honesty</title>

    <p>
      You are allowed to collaborate on the homework since this is a
      good way to learn together.. However, you must be academically
      honest and adhere to the expectations for collaboration.  A good
      self-test is this: am I using collaboration for greater
      understanding of course content?  If yes, you are likely being
      academically honest.  If, however, you are using collaboration
      to find answers that you don’t understand in order to gain
      “points”, you are likely being academically dishonest.
    </p>

    <p>
      To help support you in being a student of honesty and integrity,
      here are our guidelines for collaboration on written homework:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            “Collaboration” means “working together at roughly the
            same stage of the exercise”.  It’s not a collaboration if
            one person does the work and then shares the completed
            product with another.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            You may ask me at any time up to 24 hours before a
            homework set is due about the ideas in an exercise and
            even for hints, provided you have made an honest attempt
            at the exercise before asking me.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            You must write your solutions in your own words, and the
            words you write need to make sense to you.  You should be
            able to explain your thinking aloud to me if I were to ask
            you about it.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            You may not collaborate with people outside our class on
            homework exercises: not other students, not tutors in the
            math center, not other professors.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            You may not use internet resources other than our textbook
            and Sage: not Google generally, not Chegg, not ChatGPT,
            not other online “help” resources.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            You may not copy from any other source (another student or
            the internet).  Again: you can ask me for help and
            support.  Please do this instead of resorting to any kind
            of academic dishonesty.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Writing mathematics well</title>

    <p>
      Here is an example from one of a recent MTH 204 course.  There’s
      a screenshot of a portion of one problem below, and the full
      problem solution in the example link above.
    </p>

    <image source="images/hmk-sample.png" width="90%">
      <shortdescription>A photograph of exemplary student work that
      demonstrates the principles described below</shortdescription>
      <description>
        <p>A photograph of exemplary student work that
        demonstrates the principles described below</p>
      </description>
    </image>

    <p>
      Here's why this is well done:

      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The writer states the question they are responding to and
            provides detailed thinking about their solution.  Full
            reasoning is provided!
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Every thought is a complete sentence with subject and verb
            (the “equals” sign is a verb).
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            They use proper notation that follows standard
            mathematical conventions
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If you read the full example, you see that their
            answers/conclusions are clear and easy to find.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Overall Expectations</title>

    <p>For each of these assignments, here are expectations for how
    you present your work.

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use your best handwriting.  Work in pencil.  (Typeset work
          is certainly acceptable, but not required.)
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Provide a careful statement of each problem.  (Writing
          simply “#3” and then your answer is insufficient; it is not
          necessary to re-state every word, but you should at least
          provide a summary to indicate the context.  Clearly state
          the exercise number prior to every problem statement:
          “Exercise #3: Consider each matrix below …”.)
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          As noted above in the “writing mathematics” section,
          explanations are required: write in complete sentences,
          using correct spelling, punctuation, and grammar.  The
          reasoning that leads to answers is at least as important as
          the answers that result.  For example, you might write
          “Through row operations, we see that x = 3, y = -2, z = 7,
          and thus the original system has a unique solution.”  Every
          homework exercise should have at least one complete sentence
          that either states what you plan to do or what you have
          found.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Whenever a picture or image may be helpful, include one.
          And label each appropriately; an image without labels lacks
          meaning.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use correct mathematical language.  We will place key
          emphasis on language throughout the course.  For instance,
          from MTH 204 it would be valid to say “Thus, we have shown
          that the system of equations is inconsistent,” but it would
          be incorrect to say “Thus, we have shown that the matrix is
          inconsistent.”  The term inconsistent applies to a system of
          equations, but not a matrix itself.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          For most problems, you should think of your work in two
          phases: (a) figure out what’s going on mathematically, which
          could involve crossing out work or backtracking, and (b)
          writing up your thinking carefully.  Communication is
          extremely important so please think about separating these
          two tasks.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    </p>

    <p>
      These assignments are usually not the type that you can sit down
      and do all of the problems the day they are due.  Rather, they
      will take careful thought well in advance.  Working regularly
      and consistently over several days’ time will serve you well.
    </p>
    <p>
      Your best work is expected on each homework assignment.
      Planning ahead and giving yourself an appropriate amount of time
      to work will enable you to meet these standards.  Consider these
      assignments your opportunity to show me how well you understand
      recent material.
    </p>
  </paragraphs>
</section>
